‘Our deepest condolences go out to the families and friends of the deceased,’ Philadelphia Mayor Michael Nutter said during a press conference Tuesday. ‘I ask all Philadelphians to remember those who perished and their families in their prayers and thoughts.’

While city officials and the victims’ loved ones began picking up the pieces in the aftermath of the tragedy, new questions were being raised about the cause of the collapse.

It was revealed Thursday that nearly a month before the deadly collapse that ended the lives of six people, the City of Philadelphia had been made aware of potentially unsafe demolition practices at the site.

NBC Philadelphia reported that Center City resident Stephen Field, 49, called the municipal hotline on May 6 to express his concerns that the demolitions crew dismantling a building at 2134 Market Street used no safety equipment and had no protection for pedestrians.

