The 49-year, however, insists that he witnessed crews doing demolition work on both sites before he called the helpline.

In a press release this afternoon, Williams said that the city will now begin conducting 'proactive inspections' of all private demolitions.

Philadelphia Mayor Michael Nutter pledged a 'wide-ranging' investigation into the collapse.

John Dougherty, head of Local 98 of the electrical workers' union, called the deadly collapse a 'sad metaphor' for the city's construction process, adding that his group had been concerned in recent years with similar demolition sites.

The collapse of the building left six people dead, and in the hours after the tragic incident, their stories slowly began to emerge as their families struggled to come to terms with their loss.

Anne Bryan, 24, was a first-year student at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts who was described by teachers there as ‘dynamic, inquisitive and smart.’

